Dialogue: 0,0:00:00.00,0:00:06.85,Default,,0,0,0,,The most crucial moment in life is during decision making.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:08.22,0:00:12.99,Default,,0,0,0,,The Pacific War taught us the preciousness of peace.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:13.34,0:00:18.57,Default,,0,0,0,,But also instilled \Nnumerous lessons on how to live.{unsure, lit is "for the sake of living, precepts, numerous left behind"}
Dialogue: 0,0:00:23.37,0:00:30.38,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(100,700)\c&H0007DF&\fs100\b1\bord0\blur1}Animentary\N{\b\c&HE0DBF3&}Decision
Dialogue: 0,0:00:34.89,0:00:41.98,Default,,0,0,30,,Wit is your weapon{honestly no clue what is megurase here, deepl says "rack one's brain"}\NRemember to use your head{智恵をめぐらせ 頭を使え}
Dialogue: 0,0:00:41.98,0:00:49.84,Default,,0,0,30,,Repress your anguish, \NIf you are a man{悩み抜け抜け 男なら}
Dialogue: 0,0:00:49.84,0:00:58.24,Default,,0,0,30,,One decision is enough \NTo make others cry or laugh{泣くも笑うも 決断ひとつ}
Dialogue: 0,0:00:58.24,0:01:05.65,Default,,0,0,30,,If you win, don't hold your head high, \NIf you lose, don't cry{勝っておごるな 敗れて泣くな}
Dialogue: 0,0:01:05.65,0:01:13.55,Default,,0,0,30,,Men, don't you ever let others see your tears{男 涙は見せぬもの}
Comment: 0,0:01:34.91,0:01:34.95,Default,,0,0,0,,{ch}
Dialogue: 0,0:01:36.93,0:01:42.64,Default,,0,0,0,,The Guadalcanal campaign, that would later come to be remembered as the nastiest engagement of the Pacific War, {disastrous; tragic; miserable; wretched; pitiful; woeful}
Dialogue: 0,0:01:42.64,0:01:45.68,Default,,0,0,0,,was reaching its zenith in November 1942.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:45.68,0:01:49.44,Default,,0,0,0,,With the American mastery of sea and air \Nbeing practically uncontested,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:49.44,0:01:52.43,Default,,0,0,0,,the relief efforts couldn't make it to the front lines.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:52.43,0:01:55.83,Default,,0,0,0,,30,000 Japanese soldiers were still on Guadalcanal.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:55.83,0:01:59.06,Default,,0,0,0,,But hunger, malaria, and death plagued the island.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:59.06,0:02:02.35,Default,,0,0,0,,So they were left no choice, but to patiently wait for relief.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:04.24,0:02:11.07,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese side was denied any other means of supply, \Nexcept covert nighttime submarine delivery.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:11.58,0:02:13.71,Default,,0,0,0,,That's when, as a last ditch measure,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:13.71,0:02:18.53,Default,,0,0,0,,the plan to use fast destroyers \Nto supply the troops via oil drums was devised.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:18.53,0:02:25.14,Default,,0,0,0,,To be precise, watertight oil drums, filled with provisions and medicine, were tied together with a rope.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:25.14,0:02:29.73,Default,,0,0,0,,The destroyers would then jettison those \Ninto the sea near the shore.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:29.73,0:02:35.68,Sign,,0,0,270,,{\c&HE0EEEE&\bord0\b1\blur1}Episode 19 \N{\fs110}Battle of Tassafaronga
Dialogue: 0,0:02:54.16,0:03:00.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Prior to her departure on November 28th, \Nin the officers mess of the flagship Naganami,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:00.84,0:03:03.74,Default,,0,0,0,,on anchor in the forward base of Shortland,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:03.74,0:03:10.35,Default,,0,0,0,,a final banquet was organized for the captains of the recently formed task force of 8 destroyers,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:10.35,0:03:13.76,Default,,0,0,0,,including the commanding officer, Tanaka Raizo.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:14.36,0:03:18.72,Default,,0,0,0,,With the local planning officer \Nfrom the Imperial Headquarters also attending.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:19.93,0:03:22.95,Default,,0,0,0,,A total of 1098 drums have been loaded. {/has ?}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:22.95,0:03:26.79,Default,,0,0,0,,With exception of the patrol ship Takanami, the flagship Naganami, and the Makinami,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:26.79,0:03:32.79,Default,,0,0,0,,each one of the 5 ships, Oyashio, Kuroshio, Kawakaze, Suzukaze, and Kagero are loaded with about 220 drums. {nc what's bunsai}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:33.94,0:03:38.94,Default,,0,0,0,,That's good. But as I've just noticed, torpedoes and cannons can't be used with all those drums around.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:38.94,0:03:41.32,Default,,0,0,0,,We'll leave the fighting to the patrol ships.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:41.32,0:03:43.64,Default,,0,0,0,,They'll buy us time to drop the drums safely.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:43.64,0:03:46.49,Default,,0,0,0,,And then, we'll have a free hand \Nto do the one thing we excel at. {その間に無事ドラム艦を投下し、その後で存分に日頃の腕を振るってもらう。 - lit is "[if we encounter the enemy, the patrols would fight them off,] meanwhile we drop the barrels safely and have someone show off their habitual/daily skill/proficiency to their heart's content" - very unsure, but assumed "and after we drop the drums, our crews will engage spectacularly in a skillful night battle, that we've trained them for daily" because that's how it was irl}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:46.49,0:03:50.14,Default,,0,0,0,,So we're like a shipping agency now. \NThe petty officers also complained this morning:
Dialogue: 0,0:03:50.14,0:03:55.02,Default,,0,0,0,,"Rear Admiral Tanaka drilled us so intensely, we even earned the nickname of the Devil's 2nd Torpedo Squadron,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:55.02,0:03:56.90,Default,,0,0,0,,all that to become a shipping agency?"
Dialogue: 0,0:03:57.98,0:03:59.97,Default,,0,0,0,,You've complained about it too, haven't you?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:00.97,0:04:05.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Still, you can't feed the soldiers in Guadalcanal \Nwith just half a loaf of bread.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:05.47,0:04:08.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. I understand that myself, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:08.56,0:04:09.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Furthermore,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:11.51,0:04:15.07,Default,,0,0,0,,it's 300 nautical miles from Shortland to Guadalcanal.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:15.07,0:04:20.21,Default,,0,0,0,,If we don't make it back to this halfway point \N150 nautical miles away before daybreak,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:15.07,0:04:23.09,Sign,,0,0,0,,{Ignoring signs, too much motion}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:20.21,0:04:23.09,Default,,0,0,0,,the enemy will chase us from their base on Guadalcanal.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:23.09,0:04:29.08,Default,,0,0,0,,That's why it's essential that we drop the drums \Noff Guadalcanal by midnight. {/2400}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:32.50,0:04:35.09,Default,,0,0,0,,That's my only request. \NThe rest is up to you.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:36.02,0:04:37.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Commander.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:37.61,0:04:39.09,Default,,0,0,0,,What is it, staff officer?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:39.09,0:04:44.63,Default,,0,0,0,,From what I've heard so far, it appears that you're \Nnot expecting to encounter the enemy at all.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:44.63,0:04:47.64,Default,,0,0,0,,I never said that. \NOf course, they might show up.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:47.64,0:04:49.64,Default,,0,0,0,,No, I'm sure they will.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:49.64,0:04:51.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Then tell us the plan for a case like that.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:54.65,0:04:58.17,Default,,0,0,0,,In a case like that, I trust these gentlemen \Nto handle the situation.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:58.65,0:05:00.66,Default,,0,0,0,,They're worth their salt. {lit: being a match for a thousand; being a mighty warrior (combatant, player)​}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:00.66,0:05:02.15,Default,,0,0,0,,That's just irresponsible!
Dialogue: 0,0:05:02.15,0:05:08.16,Default,,0,0,0,,When you walk, do you command your feet \N"right foot forward, left foot forward" each time?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:09.16,0:05:12.75,Default,,0,0,0,,If you didn't like my feet metaphor, \Nlet's change the subject.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:13.75,0:05:19.31,Default,,0,0,0,,When the enemy swings his sword at a kendo master does he command his hand to "block it this way" each time?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:19.31,0:05:21.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Doesn't his hand go there automatically?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:21.90,0:05:26.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Whether or not his hand will manage to receive it \Ndepends on regular training.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:26.13,0:05:30.41,Default,,0,0,0,,That's exactly why I've been drilling \Nthis 2nd Torpedo Squadron like mad.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:30.41,0:05:33.77,Default,,0,0,0,,They're no mere shipping agency. You'll see. {unsure why they laugh, maybe some joke here, but I don't get it: take a look}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:54.31,0:05:57.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Chief Navigator.\NAre you sure that nautical chart is accurate?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:58.23,0:05:59.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Good question.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:59.83,0:06:04.59,Default,,0,0,0,,After all, those Brits produced it 15 years ago. \NIt might very well be off in certain spots.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:04.59,0:06:07.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Hey, hey. Are you sure we're not heading \Ninto one of those "certain spots"?
Dialogue: 0,0:06:08.15,0:06:10.71,Default,,0,0,0,,As long as we see the sun, we won't get lost.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:17.12,0:06:18.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh, just you leave it to me.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:19.42,0:06:21.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, leave the boat to the boatman, they say. {船に乗りゃ、船頭任せ - a proverb: "When on board a boat, leave it to the ferryman"; the other one I know is "let the cobbler stick to his last"}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:22.31,0:06:23.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Though it makes perfect sense to us, {no clue what he means: though I say leave this to me,}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:23.90,0:06:28.22,Default,,0,0,0,,that heated exchange between Chief Tanaka \Nand the HQ officer yesterday was helluva fun.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:28.22,0:06:31.47,Default,,0,0,0,,An HQ upstart with no notion \Nof the actual situation, that's who he is. {lit: a guy from the capital who doesn't know the local area}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:32.40,0:06:33.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Chief Navigator, the sun!
Dialogue: 0,0:06:33.60,0:06:35.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Finally out? About time! {nc what's before itadaki}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:37.20,0:06:37.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Time?
Dialogue: 0,0:06:37.97,0:06:39.11,Default,,0,0,0,,12:03.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:42.69,0:06:45.53,Default,,0,0,0,,A bit off, after all. \NChange of course!
Dialogue: 0,0:06:46.16,0:06:49.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Bearing - 175 degrees. \NFull to starboard! {nc whats orose, believing HA}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:04.34,0:07:06.98,Default,,0,0,0,,I hope the enemy shows up soon.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:07.34,0:07:08.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Enemy plane!
Dialogue: 0,0:07:09.41,0:07:11.81,Default,,0,0,0,,331 degrees 20 minutes! {no clue what's 20 here, he doesn't actually say minutes; maybe it's not futamaru at all, not in hA}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:13.80,0:07:16.81,Default,,0,0,0,,B-17 bomber! One plane!
Dialogue: 0,0:07:21.19,0:07:23.05,Default,,0,0,0,,Prepare for anti-aircraft combat.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:23.05,0:07:26.46,Default,,0,0,0,,All crew, anti-aircraft combat! \NMan your positions! {believing HA, nc what's actually ichinitsuke}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:02.00,0:08:03.28,Default,,0,0,0,,They saw us.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:03.28,0:08:04.67,Default,,0,0,0,,I suppose.
Dialogue: 1,0:08:04.67,0:08:10.40,Default,,0,0,0,,At the same time, the American side knew about the Japanese relief fleet, supplying Guadalcanal at night.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:04.67,0:08:13.28,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fs30\c&HEFEEF9&\blur1\3c&HE3D2BB&\pos(1059,956)}Guadalcanal
Dialogue: 0,0:08:04.67,0:08:13.28,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fs30\c&HEFEEF9&\blur1\3c&HE4CEB7&\pos(154,320)}Bougainville
Dialogue: 0,0:08:04.67,0:08:13.28,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fs30\c&HEFEEF9&\blur1\3c&H151214&\pos(283,520)}Shortland Archipelago
Dialogue: 0,0:08:04.67,0:08:13.28,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fs30\c&HEFEEF9&\blur1\3c&H151214&\pos(972,740)}Savo Island
Dialogue: 1,0:08:10.40,0:08:15.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Their sailors nicknamed it "The Tokyo Express" \Nand harassed it relentlessly, sinking many of the convoys.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:16.41,0:08:22.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Among those was Task Force 67, led by Rear Admiral \NCarlton Wright from on board USS Minneapolis,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:22.37,0:08:27.19,Default,,0,0,0,,consisting of 4 heavy cruisers, \N1 light cruiser, and 6 destroyers.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:27.19,0:08:31.67,Default,,0,0,0,,A fleet numbering 11 ships total \Nthat had already caught wind of the Japanese strategy
Dialogue: 0,0:08:31.67,0:08:35.49,Default,,0,0,0,,of supplying Guadalcanal with drums, \Ndelivered by the 2nd Torpedo Squadron,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:35.49,0:08:38.20,Default,,0,0,0,,was waiting for its chance to strike. {to be ready and waiting; to be on the alert; to be on the watch​}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:38.20,0:08:40.61,Default,,0,0,0,,As reported previously, the enemy numbers 8 ships.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:40.61,0:08:44.25,Default,,0,0,0,,We'll go with the strategy that Togo \Nonce used in the Battle of Tsushima.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:44.83,0:08:48.26,Default,,0,0,0,,However, since the enemy excels at night battles,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:48.26,0:08:52.26,Default,,0,0,0,,we'll illuminate them with flares \Nfrom our cruisers' seaplanes and destroy them.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:52.26,0:08:54.26,Default,,0,0,0,,Going with "a rat in the trap," right? {fukuro can be "dead end/plot of land surrounded by water" so I guess they mean this, was It's "a rat in a trap". in HA; I think "a deer in the headlights" also kinda fits}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:54.65,0:08:59.24,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese proverb goes, \N"A cornered rat will bite the cat." Be careful. {a cornered rat will bite the cat; one who is cornered will fight like a devil}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:59.24,0:09:03.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Moreover, even though it's just a destroyer squadron, \Nit is {\i1}the{\i0} 2nd Torpedo Squadron, drilled to hell and back.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:03.64,0:09:05.27,Default,,0,0,0,,There's no telling what they'll do.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:05.27,0:09:10.07,Default,,0,0,0,,However, we have radar. \NSomething that's still completely unheard-of in Japan.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:10.07,0:09:12.87,Default,,0,0,0,,They rely on their eyes, \Neven when night fighting.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:12.87,0:09:17.29,Default,,0,0,0,,As you all know, in a naval battle, \Nhe who spots the enemy first has the upper hand. {/knows the enemy position}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:17.98,0:09:21.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Of course, the Japanese fleet also changed its course.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:21.20,0:09:24.62,Default,,0,0,0,,They decided to infiltrate \Nthe Guadalcanal area from the front.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:24.62,0:09:29.95,Default,,0,0,0,,4 nautical miles west of Savo Island, \Nthey've been approaching on a 180 degree course. {no clue what it means here, 180 degrees is basically backwards so it doesn't make sense from any point of view; maybe he means "they've decided to do a 180 later" bc that's what happened irl, but he clearly speaks in past tense here; 進路180度でガダルカナル島前面に侵入することにした}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:59.55,0:10:00.89,Default,,0,0,0,,What time is it?
Dialogue: 0,0:10:01.28,0:10:02.03,Default,,0,0,0,,22:00, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:02.03,0:10:04.04,Default,,0,0,0,,2 more hours?
Dialogue: 0,0:10:04.04,0:10:07.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. It seems, we'll finish the mission \Nwithout the enemy discovering us.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:14.61,0:10:17.05,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir. A transmission from the 8th Fleet HQ.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:17.53,0:10:18.18,Default,,0,0,0,,What is it?
Dialogue: 0,0:10:18.78,0:10:23.25,Default,,0,0,0,,From radio traffic monitoring, we've concluded that the enemy is informed of your fleet's actions.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:23.25,0:10:27.06,Default,,0,0,0,,If the enemy engages you, forget about supplies, \Nconcentrate on destroying the enemy.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:27.06,0:10:31.06,Default,,0,0,0,,I see. If we encounter the hostile fleet, \Njettison the drums and fight with all we got?
Dialogue: 0,0:10:31.06,0:10:32.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:32.06,0:10:34.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Good job. Please inform the other ships too.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:34.59,0:10:36.05,Default,,0,0,0,,Roger. Will do.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:38.59,0:10:43.20,Default,,0,0,0,,I hope they don't find us before we drop the provisions. \NThe soldiers on the island are waiting.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:43.66,0:10:46.70,Default,,0,0,0,,We'll be sure to run as fast as we can until then.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:46.70,0:10:48.71,Default,,0,0,0,,How about sinking them, instead of running?
Dialogue: 0,0:10:49.15,0:10:56.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Priorities first. We're a shipping agency today. Our priority is the soldiers on the island. The customer is king and all. {actually otokui is "regular customer; valued client​"}
Dialogue: 0,0:11:10.71,0:11:13.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Those guys are quick to escape. \NYou still haven't found the Japanese?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:13.63,0:11:14.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Just a little more time...
Dialogue: 0,0:11:14.73,0:11:18.74,Default,,0,0,0,,They know that if they don't come by midnight, \Nour land based planes would be after them. {no clue what he means: 24時までに来なければ基地の飛行機に捕まるのを知っているからな - probably that the japanese have to leave or else the planes from tulagi would reach them after the sun rises;}
Dialogue: 0,0:11:18.74,0:11:21.19,Default,,0,0,0,,And if they left that area, they {\i1}must{\i0} come here. {again unsure: 出撃しているなら必ず来る - if they're on the sortie, they'll definitely come}
Dialogue: 0,0:11:21.19,0:11:22.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes...
Dialogue: 0,0:11:22.09,0:11:24.74,Default,,0,0,0,,The Lord is smiling upon us.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:24.74,0:11:29.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Under this rain cloud, \Nthe Japs can see out to 4,000 meters at best.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:29.02,0:11:33.40,Default,,0,0,0,,While we have radar with 24,000 meters of coverage.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:33.40,0:11:36.63,Default,,0,0,0,,That difference of 20,000 meters \Ncan give us a crucial edge over them. {to beat someone to the punch; to get the drop on (someone); to forestall}
Dialogue: 0,0:11:43.10,0:11:43.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Is this...
Dialogue: 0,0:11:43.95,0:11:49.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. This certainly is the enemy ship, 6,300 meters away. \NAt a point about 8 nautical miles from Tassafaronga.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:49.68,0:11:52.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Alright, prepare for battle! \NMan your positions!
Dialogue: 0,0:11:55.74,0:11:59.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Eight ships. Once they're in position, \Nwe'll wipe them all in one fell swoop. {barely hear anything, mostly a guess: we'll attract/draw near all together and kill with one move}
Dialogue: 0,0:12:07.75,0:12:10.75,Default,,0,0,0,,One last push. The island is visible already.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:11.43,0:12:14.17,Default,,0,0,0,,It seems, the enemy never got on our tail, after all.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:14.17,0:12:16.13,Default,,0,0,0,,No, we've certainly been caught.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:16.73,0:12:19.18,Default,,0,0,0,,But we still have no idea where they'll come from.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:19.61,0:12:21.99,Default,,0,0,0,,It's a fight between a blind man and a seeing one.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:21.99,0:12:24.18,Default,,0,0,0,,If we can just deliver 10 days' worth of supplies... {no clue what he means: just prepare 10 days of food / 食料10日の準備だけはしておく}
Dialogue: 0,0:12:24.59,0:12:26.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, understood.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:26.17,0:12:28.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Prepare to drop. Signal every vessel! {nc whats last word}
Dialogue: 0,0:12:31.79,0:12:38.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Even knowing that the Americans have them on their radar, \NTanaka's Fleet drew closer to the island.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:39.50,0:12:43.22,Default,,0,0,0,,At exactly 23:16...
Dialogue: 0,0:12:59.51,0:13:04.13,Default,,0,0,0,,45 degrees to the left! Two black shapes! \NLooks like an enemy destroyer.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:04.13,0:13:07.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Good. The blind just became sighted. {lit: with this, the blind opened his eyes}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:07.32,0:13:08.71,Default,,0,0,0,,How far are they?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:08.71,0:13:09.64,Default,,0,0,0,,6,000 meters!
Dialogue: 0,0:13:10.41,0:13:11.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Alright, we got it!
Dialogue: 0,0:13:11.65,0:13:15.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Report to flagship. \NStart a simultaneous torpedo-cannon attack! {wiki: A lookout for Takanami, who was on guard duty with a single ship, spotted an enemy destroyer at a distance of 6,000 meters, 45 degrees to the left. Immediately, Takanami issued an emergency warning to the Japanese fleet that the enemy had been detected, but the distance was too close and the Japanese army, which was preparing to land, was almost attacked by surprise. Takanami's captain, Lieutenant Colonel Masami Ogura, immediately gave the order for ``simultaneous battle with left gun and torpedo'' and began an attack movement.}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:15.10,0:13:16.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Chief navigator, bearings! {eye measurement; measure with eye}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:16.53,0:13:16.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Roger!
Dialogue: 0,0:13:18.82,0:13:21.06,Default,,0,0,0,,7 destroyer-like enemy ships.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:21.06,0:13:23.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Cardinal direction - 45 degrees to the left. {nc whats kaku after houi and why he says "yonijuugo do" - that'd be "425 degrees"}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:23.18,0:13:25.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Enemy speed: 24 knots at 50 degrees! {again no clue why he says "24 knots 50" and what to make of 50, maybe "24.5"? seems too precise for such a distance. unfortunately, this is not in wiki}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:27.32,0:13:28.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Prepare long lances at 50 degrees! {no clue, choushaku may have something to do with length so it's probably "long-range torpedoes"; no idea whats the last word, maybe "50" again but still unclear what it means; was "Get ready" in HA; maybe this goju is something like a naval code/etiquette to put in the end of a sentence, like "prepare torpedoes, over" but they're not talking on the radio so idk}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:33.68,0:13:35.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Adjust the settings. I'm counting on you! {no clue what's before tanomu, was "It's all set. I'll leave it." in HA, I don't see how it may have anything to do with makeup/decoration; dressing; veneer}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:39.08,0:13:41.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Why do you press forward without breaking formation?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:41.67,0:13:44.80,Default,,0,0,0,,This way, we'll be standing naked in the enemy's sight!
Dialogue: 0,0:13:44.80,0:13:50.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. However, our supply mission comes first. \NJettisoning the provisions now would be a terrible waste.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:50.51,0:13:52.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Our soldiers are waiting there.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:52.31,0:13:56.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Our mission is to sink as many enemy ships as possible!
Dialogue: 0,0:13:56.52,0:13:59.07,Default,,0,0,0,,We'll do that too. \NBut now, let's focus on supplies.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:59.46,0:14:02.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Can you even hear yourself?! \NThe enemy is right in front of us!
Dialogue: 0,0:14:02.60,0:14:04.66,Default,,0,0,0,,We'll drop the supplies as close as we can. {lit: let's do it as far as we can}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:04.66,0:14:08.09,Default,,0,0,0,,There, the island can already see us. \NThey're signaling.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:15.54,0:14:18.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Just a little closer to here!
Dialogue: 0,0:14:18.27,0:14:20.05,Default,,0,0,0,,Please, Navy boys!
Dialogue: 0,0:14:28.28,0:14:29.93,Default,,0,0,0,,The enemy has 11 ships total.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:37.44,0:14:40.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Captain, wanna have a shot from our usual bottle?
Dialogue: 0,0:14:40.98,0:14:45.45,Default,,0,0,0,,No, I'm on duty today. \NWait until we complete the delivery. {/until we deliver provisions to our customers}{no clue what's the first sentence, was "I'm standing this time" in HA, could be "to pass (of time); to elapse" but it can't be used to say "I'll pass on drinking"}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:45.96,0:14:47.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Can we fire, Captain?
Dialogue: 0,0:14:47.53,0:14:49.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Patience! Just a little more.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:53.45,0:14:58.73,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\blur1\fade(2500,0)\pos(771,204)}Savo Island
Dialogue: 0,0:14:53.45,0:14:58.73,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\blur1\fade(2500,0)\pos(298,898)}Guadalcanal
Dialogue: 0,0:15:03.72,0:15:05.94,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese haven't noticed us yet?
Dialogue: 0,0:15:05.94,0:15:09.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. And we can see the side \Nof their first ship clearly. Let's shoot.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:09.47,0:15:12.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Wait. We'll annihilate them together \Nonce all ships are in range.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:20.77,0:15:23.42,Default,,0,0,0,,I hope they'll be alright after coming that far. {actually not hope, but "if they make it that far, it's alright" so maybe he means "we can handle it from there, turn back now"}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:23.88,0:15:26.57,Default,,0,0,0,,But look there. \NThe enemy surrounded them.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:28.03,0:15:31.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Ah! Could it be that our boys are still unaware?
Dialogue: 0,0:15:31.01,0:15:32.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Hey!
Dialogue: 0,0:15:32.09,0:15:34.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Idiot. Think they'll hear you from here? {going by HA's "They can never hear your yelling.", I hear "no matter how much you doratta (could mean gong), think they'll hear?"}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:34.14,0:15:36.10,Default,,0,0,0,,They're sacrificing themselves for us! {/become prey}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:43.16,0:15:44.31,Default,,0,0,0,,That's ridiculous.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:44.31,0:15:46.14,Default,,0,0,0,,How can you call yourself a commander?
Dialogue: 0,0:15:46.14,0:15:51.18,Default,,0,0,0,,The battle is all about waiting for your chance! \NDon't tell me you've forgotten such a rudimentary thing.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:51.18,0:15:53.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Planning officer, enough already.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:55.56,0:15:57.05,Default,,0,0,0,,The torpedoes are incoming. {lit: they're coming/here}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:57.05,0:15:58.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Turn the rudder.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:02.87,0:16:05.87,Default,,0,0,0,,The enemy made their move!\NRear Admiral, it's time to make a decision! {no idea whatsoever what's in the first part, same in HA}
Dialogue: 0,0:16:05.87,0:16:08.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Planning officer, this decision is mine to make.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:13.66,0:16:14.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay. Do it.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:14.97,0:16:17.21,Default,,0,0,0,,All ships fire at once. \NClosest target first. {lit: first ship #1 - means takanami because she was detached and the one that discovered the us first}
Dialogue: 0,0:16:23.30,0:16:25.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Look at that, the enemy is going for it.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:25.48,0:16:27.34,Default,,0,0,0,,But that alone won't be enough.{maybe "that one didn't hit"}
Dialogue: 0,0:16:41.87,0:16:45.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Rear Admiral! Take a look at that! \NTakanami won't last much longer! {lit "is being a prey/victim"}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:50.55,0:17:52.67,Default,,0,0,0,,What is wrong with you... {lit: a man like you}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:53.05,0:17:54.26,Default,,0,0,0,,You saved us!
Dialogue: 0,0:17:54.26,0:17:56.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you!
Dialogue: 0,0:18:05.82,0:18:08.29,Default,,0,0,0,,We've finished dropping the provisions!
Dialogue: 0,0:18:08.29,0:18:10.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Good. Signal all ships...
Dialogue: 0,0:18:10.68,0:18:12.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Charge the enemy with all we got!
Dialogue: 0,0:18:12.44,0:18:14.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Open fire!
Dialogue: 0,0:18:14.55,0:18:16.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Now captain?
Dialogue: 0,0:18:16.38,0:18:17.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Go ahead!
Dialogue: 0,0:18:17.23,0:18:18.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Finally!
Dialogue: 0,0:18:18.40,0:18:20.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Set depth to 3 meters! Target the third ship. {believing HA but I very much doubt it, no clue whats the last word really}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:26.04,0:18:28.46,Default,,0,0,0,,I can't see anything behind such high splashes! {believing HA's "The pillar of fire is too much and cannot be seen well." except I think he means water/ "柱が立ちすぎてよう見えんな"}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:28.46,0:18:32.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Alright! The one that just fired. Shoot at that ship! {Alright. The one you just shot. Again. in HA; what I wrote makes sense sinceit's a night battle}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:55.41,0:18:57.26,Default,,0,0,0,,We can almost see the whites of their eyes. {no clue what he means: 敵さんの顔もよう分かる / We can see the face of the enemy well. in HA, maybe he means "we're close enough to see them well", maybe "I can already imagine the looks on their faces", maybe "I know my enemy well"}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:57.26,0:18:59.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Prepare for a concentrated attack! {nc what's first word, was "launch" in HA}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:24.45,0:19:30.12,Default,,0,0,0,,The torpedoes of the well-drilled 2nd Torpedo Squadron \Nwere powerful and accurate.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:31.02,0:19:36.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Because of that, all cruisers except Honolulu \Nhave been hit with one torpedo at least.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:36.41,0:19:42.61,Default,,0,0,0,,On the American side, one heavy cruiser was sunk, \Nwith 3 more getting thoroughly thrashed.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:14.74,0:20:17.58,Default,,0,0,0,,They knew that the rearguard was still encumbered. {no clue, probably "裏まで荷物を積んでたんですよ/loaded with the luggage all the way to the back" but no idea what it means; was "They used to load the luggage" in HA which is just as nonsensical}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:17.58,0:20:21.76,Default,,0,0,0,,These guys knew what they needed to do \Nwithout any orders from above, planning officer. {あいつらは命令されなくともちゃんとやるでしょう}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:21.76,0:20:24.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Captain, we have to save Takanami now.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:24.89,0:20:30.87,Default,,0,0,0,,They've done well, but Oyashio and Kuroshio have already beaten the enemy off. We can . Send them there. {to be satisfied; to find peace of mind; to feel good}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:30.87,0:20:32.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Roger. I will pass down the order.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:38.72,0:20:41.21,Default,,0,0,0,,How did it go? It's become a little quiet, I see?
Dialogue: 0,0:20:41.21,0:20:42.49,Default,,0,0,0,,We won.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:43.17,0:20:45.22,Default,,0,0,0,,The enemy is all but wiped out.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:46.53,0:20:47.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh?
Dialogue: 0,0:20:47.24,0:20:48.62,Default,,0,0,0,,We won?
Dialogue: 0,0:20:48.62,0:20:49.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Of course.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:49.93,0:20:51.70,Default,,0,0,0,,And what are our losses?
Dialogue: 0,0:20:51.70,0:20:53.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Only Takanami.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:53.04,0:20:54.58,Default,,0,0,0,,That's a relief.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:55.38,0:21:00.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Chief Surgeon, the Oyashio and Kuroshio are coming \Nto Takanami's rescue now. You should come with them.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:00.07,0:21:05.08,Default,,0,0,0,,By god, when I get there I'll make sure nobody is slacking off. My revenge for having nothing to do when we drill. {no clue what he means, was "Thank you for that. I can't handle it anymore. I usually play, so I got a punishment." in HA; いや もう手が回らんですよ 普段遊んでる場地ですな - "I'm grateful for that, no, already to leave nothing undone; to give good service; to attend to everything; to see to something properly​. Usually/normally playing divine retrubution/punishment"; I could only conclude that he means "thank god, when I get there I'll make sure nobody is slacking off, as a revenge for me being left with nothing to do during our usual drills"}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:05.92,0:21:07.57,Default,,0,0,0,,By the way, any idea where Captain is?
Dialogue: 0,0:21:08.00,0:21:11.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. Sleeping in front of the Chief Navigator's cabin.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:11.63,0:21:12.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Sleeping?
Dialogue: 0,0:21:21.48,0:21:22.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Captain.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:25.31,0:21:28.31,Default,,0,0,0,,I came to raise a toast with you.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:32.31,0:21:35.00,Default,,0,0,0,,You don't have to refuse anymore.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:35.94,0:21:37.32,Default,,0,0,0,,You're off duty now. {very unsure, but assumed 願が解けました - your vow has been lifted; was "I feel relaxed." in  ha}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:53.68,0:22:01.23,Song,,0,0,0,,{\fade(3300,0)}...scenes {full version of poem here: http://www.kangin.or.jp/learning/text/japanese/k_A2_043.html}
Dialogue: 0,0:22:01.23,0:22:13.87,Song,,0,0,0,,Because if not, my wise teacher,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:14.89,0:22:26.67,Song,,0,0,0,,I'll remember our expedition
Dialogue: 0,0:22:26.67,0:22:31.89,Song,,0,0,0,,And think of you...
Dialogue: 0,0:22:43.38,0:22:44.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Thanks!
Dialogue: 0,0:22:44.01,0:22:45.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you, guys!
Dialogue: 0,0:22:49.56,0:22:51.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Thanks!
Dialogue: 0,0:22:59.83,0:23:00.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:00.67,0:23:02.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Right. You did well.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:02.15,0:23:05.04,Default,,0,0,0,,I have to apologize. I was so arrogant.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:05.04,0:23:11.18,Default,,0,0,0,,I now understand the meaning of your metaphor, \Nof giving orders to your right and left leg each time.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:12.83,0:23:15.67,Default,,0,0,0,,If only we could have saved Takanami...
Dialogue: 0,0:23:20.67,0:23:26.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Thus, the Battle of Tassafaronga \Nwas over in mere 30 minutes.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:27.83,0:23:34.51,Default,,0,0,0,,It is said that Admiral Nimitz instructed all his Navy officers and men to "train, train, and train again,"
Dialogue: 0,0:23:34.51,0:23:40.37,Default,,0,0,0,,deeply impressed by the successes of the Japanese destroyer squadron.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:41.57,0:23:45.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Alongside his strategy of trusting the skill of his subordinates,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:45.63,0:23:51.48,Default,,0,0,0,,gained through rigorous drilling, and leaving everything \Nto them with full confidence, the commander
Dialogue: 0,0:23:51.48,0:23:55.33,Default,,0,0,0,,also made several very humane decisions \Nwhich earned him the respect of others. {very long and complex sentence, not sure I got it all right:  厳しい訓練から得られた部下の力を信頼し全てを安心して任せた作戦とともに高く評価されるものは指揮官の人間としての決断でもあろう}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:58.16,0:24:08.17,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(100,0)}The Pacific War taught us the preciousness of peace.\NBut also instilled numerous lessons on how to live.{太平洋戦争はわれわれに平和の尊さを教えたがまた生きるための教訓を数多くのこしている}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:09.44,0:24:11.88,Default,,0,0,0,,July 1944.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:11.88,0:24:15.27,Default,,0,0,0,,American forces began advancing \Ntowards Saipan Island.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:15.86,0:24:21.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Capturing Saipan Island would provide a base from which the B-29 long-range bombers
Dialogue: 0,0:24:21.22,0:24:25.89,Default,,0,0,0,,could attack the Japanese mainland.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:25.89,0:24:27.91,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese answer to this has been
Dialogue: 0,0:24:27.91,0:24:31.97,Default,,0,0,0,,a concentrated sortie by the Combined Fleet \Nunder the command of Vice Admiral Ozawa.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:31.97,0:24:38.41,Sign,,0,0,0,,Episode 20 \NBattle of the Philippine Sea
Dialogue: 0,0:24:32.58,0:24:36.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Witness in the next decision: \NBattle of the Philippine Sea.
Comment: 0,0:24:43.11,0:24:43.15,Default,,0,0,0,,{ch}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:44.04,0:24:48.96,Default,,0,0,50,,If you're a man, let's put your strength to test{男だったら　力を試せ}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:48.96,0:24:52.93,Default,,0,0,50,,If you are a man, keep your hopes sizzling{男だったら　希望(のぞみ)を燃やせ}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:52.93,0:24:57.23,Default,,0,0,50,,If you are a man, don't lose your heart{男だったら　くじけるな}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:57.23,0:25:05.61,Default,,0,0,50,,Because there's just you and me, a man and a man{俺もおまえも　男と男}
Dialogue: 0,0:25:05.61,0:25:14.21,Default,,0,0,50,,With crimson blood flowing in our veins all the same{おなじ真赤な　血が通う}
